**Method 4 — annotation  (attribute-style embedding)**
same source file as Method1
Annotation uses the same plain JSON as the leaf method. The only difference is the output: the signature appears as "@ypmd:provenance-string" (an attribute-style key) inside the first inner object, rather than as a plain "provenance-string" field.


mpalmero@mac provenance % curl -k -X POST 'https://195.235.93.145/function/json-signer?enclosing=annotation'  --data-binary "@source_unsigned.json"  -o source_signed_annot.json
  % Total    % Received % Xferd  Average Speed   Time    Time     Time  Current
                                 Dload  Upload   Total   Spent    Left  Speed
100   910  100   522  100   388    388    288  0:00:01  0:00:01 --:--:--   676


mpalmero@mac provenance % more source_signed_annot.json
{
  "ietf-green:sources" : {
    "source" : [ {
      "id" : "router-edge-01",
      "mechanisms" : [ "cose-provenance" ],
      "timestamp" : "2024-02-03T11:22:41Z",
      "location" : "datacenter-madrid-01",
      "energy-metrics" : {
        "power-watts" : 187.4,
        "throughput-gbps" : 38.2,
        "efficiency-gbps-per-watt" : 0.204
      }
    } ],
    "@ypmd:provenance-string" : "0oRRowNjeG1sBGdlYzIua2V5ASag9lhA9XyWv5YvF0YdNWYAll0946SsetebJc+ggW1Fp1zMGdXI5lxx3Yd/HtJr6fR7xxFp8LPqdL95iYyhFWgDoZKWrQ=="
  }
}

Output will have "@ypmd:provenance-string": "0oRRow..." inside "ietf-green:sources".

The **verifier** is the same endpoint regardless of which enclosing method was used — it auto-detects the structure.
curl -k -X POST \
  'https://195.235.93.145/function/json-verifier' \
  --data-binary "@source_signed.json"

mpalmero@mac provenance % curl -k -X POST \
  'https://195.235.93.145/function/json-verifier' \
  --data-binary "@source_signed.json"

Signature verified
mpalmero@mac provenance % curl -k -X POST \
  'https://195.235.93.145/function/json-verifier' \
  --data-binary "@source_signed_notif.json"
Signature verified
mpalmero@mac provenance % curl -k -X POST \
  'https://195.235.93.145/function/json-verifier' \
  --data-binary "@source_signed_inst.json" 
Signature verified
mpalmero@mac provenance % curl -k -X POST \
  'https://195.235.93.145/function/json-verifier' \
  --data-binary "@source_signed_annot.json"
Signature verified


The four methods need very specific top-level keys:

Method | Required top-level key | Where signature lands
-- | -- | --
leaf | anything (e.g. "ietf-green:sources") | inside the first inner object as "provenance-string"
notification | "ietf-yp-notification:envelope" | inside the envelope as "ietf-yp-provenance:provenance"
instance | "ietf-yang-instance-data:instance-data-set" | inside that object as "provenance-string"
annotation | anything | inside the first inner object as "@ypmd:provenance-string"

For the IETF proposal, the notification method is the most compelling scenario to demonstrate — it shows a controller receiving a YANG-Push stream of source-status events, verifying each one in real time, and maintaining traceability-verified per source-id. 

Recommendation: Start with leaf to confirm the JSON structure works, then try notification with the envelope wrapper.

issues.body:
Reason: the CODE BEGINS does not have the right convention

https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/rfc9907/

1.1.  Changes Since RFC 8407

  ...

   *  Updated the guidance so that the "file name" after the "<CODE
      BEGINS>" tag is mandatory.



   The "<CODE BEGINS>" tag MUST be followed by a string identifying the
   file name specified in Section 5.2 of [RFC7950].  The name string
   form that includes the revision date SHOULD be used.  The revision
   date MUST match the date used in the most recent revision of the
   module.

   The following example is for the "2016-03-20" revision of the "ietf-
   foo" module:

   <CODE BEGINS>
   file "ietf-foo@2016-03-20.yang"

       module ietf-foo {
         namespace "urn:ietf:params:xml:ns:yang:ietf-foo";
         prefix "foo";
         organization "...";
         contact "...";
         description "...";
         revision 2016-03-20 {
           description "Latest revision";
           reference "RFC FFFF: Foo Protocol";
         }
         // ... more statements
       }
   <CODE ENDS>

